Had this issue and spend some time learning so I find this...

Controllers annotated with `@Controller` return views (*HTML templates*) by default, and they are often used in combination with *Thymeleaf*, *JSP*, or other template engines.

`@RestController` is used for building web services that return data in formats like *JSON* or *XML*. 

In order to use `@Controller` you can go with -&gt;

Add `@ResponseBody` annotation below `@GetMapping` -&gt;   

```java
@Controller
public class MyController {

    @GetMapping(&quot;/message&quot;)
    @ResponseBody
    public String showMessage() {
        return &quot;Hello, this is a simple message!&quot;;
    }
}
```

