instanceof is runtime type checking but generics uses type erasure at compile time. 
That&#39;s why instanceof is not allowed to use for &lt; T &gt; but allowed to use for the raw type List. 
You may check out this tutorial about generics cannot use instanceof: https://www.tutorialspoint.com/java_generics/java_generics_no_instanceof.htm

Alternatively, there are some solutions I can think of.

Approach 1: Check the type of the first list item.
	
	if (inner instanceof List &amp;&amp; !((List) inner).isEmpty() &amp;&amp; ((List) inner).get(0) instanceof Map) {
		// You may continue to check map key and value if necessary.
	} else if (inner instanceof Map) {
		// You may continue to check map key and value if necessary.
	} else {
		throw new IllegalArgumentException(&quot;List or Map only&quot;);
	}

Approach 2: Use type casting in try catch block. 

	try {
		Map&lt;String, String&gt; map = (Map&lt;String, String&gt;) inner;
		Map.Entry&lt;String, String&gt; entry = map.entrySet().iterator().next();
		String key = entry.getKey();
		String value = entry.getValue();
		System.out.println(key + &quot; &quot; + value);
	} catch (ClassCastException e) {
		System.out.println(&quot;Object is not Map&lt;String, String&gt;&quot;);
	}

You can use Approach 2 with Approach 1 to continue to check after instanceof Map.

Approach 3: Use a wrapper class for instanceof.

	class ListWrapper extends ArrayList&lt;Map&lt;String, String&gt;&gt; { 
		//...
	}

This way takes you more efforts to implement CRUD operations.

